Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, as part of an amendment to the criminal law, the proposed annulment of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs rejected in second reading the draft amendment to reduce penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for concluding an a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not final and the court is due to decide on the sentenced woman's appeal in December.
Tymosenko describes the regime's judgment as political revenge and has provoked a process of suspicion of court bias also in the west.
The proposal to repeal paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was condemned, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
