The diet of an obese child: do not eat breakfast and take cold meats for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with overweight, 9% of schoolchildren will have above-average weight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This shows once again how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models that surround him is.
On the tables of obese children, for example, sausages are found 50% more often than in families of children of normal weight.
19% of obese people had French fries at dinner, according to the survey conducted with an awareness-raising action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In families of small and large, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most of today's schoolchildren - only 15% responded that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Investigation of 900 children
The survey was conducted during the last school year and 900 students from Czech primary schools participated.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from the sixth to third grades have enrolled in this project.
One of the determinants that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight, even obese children, is the lack of a correct diet and not enough exercise.
“Only half of the children surveyed reported eating breakfast five times a day – in case of lunch, snack, dinner, which is one of the basic principles of a good diet,” said one of the survey results.
No breakfast and charcuterie at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development it takes a few basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students’ families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been noted is that a tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that families of obese children consume more often unhealthy fries.
Almost every student - not to mention weight - drinks sugary drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children surveyed exercise regularly but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet based on options proposed according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favorite dishes are many cakes, meats and sweets.
“The most alarming is, in particular, a high preference for sweet lemonades,” the survey results indicate.
For lunch it was pasta that took the first place right in front of white meat.
The children did not want starches at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Heading to health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a control of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness session 'Obesity is not a coincidence', there was a determined willingness to move towards a healthy diet," the results of the survey said.
The most striking was, for example, with regard to sweet lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (the Czech specialty of bread flour balls or potatoes).
