How Travel Prices Have Changed Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel especially to the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a leaning towards the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter otherwise individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good acquaintance" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling to the west was denied to the "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable, however, and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The Czechs’ travels have been undergoing a major revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million days of holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the west caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel for a long time by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip was at that time to take with you your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown which finally allowed our tourists after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary increased which caused around the year 1997 another important moment.
As a result of growing demand for travel, since 1997 travel agencies have started to prepare tours with air charter links that through contracts have tremendously reduced costs compared to what was before.
In the late 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world, apart from the US, which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, was prepared from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully rank in the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008 the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person on holidays abroad including the associated charges.
