21st house in Vienna
The pavilion that has moved
D'Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with highs, lows and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
It is now open again and serves as an exhibition hall.
If one is enthusiastic about modern post-war architecture, for its clear shapes, its glass sheds, its bright and bold looks and its new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the Brussels World's Fair in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its light and suspended steel and glass construction.
Construction is considered to this day as an important step in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian World's Fair.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and its adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the south station of Vienna, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suited for a museum - no walls to hang artworks, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for as long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has decayed more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name "House of the 21st century" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvédère museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a chance from any point of view.
The new start was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian gallery Belvédère in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as an artistic skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she has carried out particularly well the works of transformation with politicians and the protection of monuments, she has obtained public funds and sponsorship.
Except for contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a café and a bookshop are there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict monitoring, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had sensibly transformed and expanded the secession of Joseph Olbracht and that he had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" place where he had seen "almost every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of its move to Vienna and by its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "a pit of energy", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was laid and the roof was replaced by a special safety glass.
Thermal bridge beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a dimmed light panel between the house and the road ensures the lighting, a bridge leading to the entrance - this is almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remained, the house is painted in a rust-protection shade of red-brown color.
And the cinema is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and inexpensive had to be found, and that also please the monuments protection office," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a raw floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
It would have been difficult with the Pavilion, “which came from Brussels,” Krischanitz said recently, a typical “Drop-in-the-City” story.
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and nevertheless wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a chance of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands precisely the newly planned "Central Station district", with offices and apartments.
And another chance may be coming: the 21st century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin temporary art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city in order to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
