A tip to get started: carefully tear this page apart and make it your bookmark.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this romantic narrative by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately describes as "a work of anti-history."
It includes some known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and material.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like," with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
“Beauty and Sorrow” summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, to doctors, paramedics and vendors.
Some of them will become heroes.
Other prisoners of war, some will lose limbs, go crazy, or lose their lives.
Their lives waver here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund's book departs from traditional history books.
He denies the idea that the First World War can only be summed up in the terrible trench warfare on the Western front.
"Beauty and sorrow" cleverly describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; a Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When cannon shots sound in the distance, and you’re a housewife, do you stay or run away?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “the lack of facts has been enhanced by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nanny in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
Versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are the most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
