7 Lessons from Steve Jobs' Lost Interview at the Movies This Week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most telling in a recently found Steve Jobs interview that will air this week in the first part of a film about major markets, is how this creative mind had understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a flowchart enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders were suffering from a "illness making them think that a great idea does 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates an idea."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds", which traces the birth of the computer, and he sits for over an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years since Steve Jobs had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in transport.
It is only after the death of Steve Jobs that a full video is found in the director's garage.
This video is the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be released on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs seems surprisingly enthusiastic here to expose technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide an accurate answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs’ perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringely’s questions, giving him a kick to speed him up and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, we find a strangely prescient aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision on the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and man-inspiring that we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then puts them into practice.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences from Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
“All these years I’ve always asked, ‘Why are you doing things?’ and the answers are constantly the same, ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to give details on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed with how costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" assessed at a glance and then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed the accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a trick to the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that used to hack phone networks and make free long-distance calls.
The device has been the subject of many writings beforehand, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We wrapped the ball with different things half a dozen times and you were screaming on the public phone and it happened to you a minute later on the public phone next door," Jobs laughed.
“We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We didn't both know much, but we invented a little thing that could control big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without that.
Steve Jobs continues by recounting a wonderful trick he and Wozniak have set up: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night posing as Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go insanely laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love for technology (and Bill Hewlett’s outreach):
At the age of 12, on the hunt for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a phone call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company’s research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the “first desktop ever designed.”
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On the improvisation of innovation:
At several moments in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products at a glance.
At the beginning of his career, while he settled to sell a few printed circuit boards, a customer asked him to assemble a complete computer.
Working on only 30 days of credit, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big arguments... they were yelling at me and saying it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that proved incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are suffocating:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industry leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
“Let’s say you worked at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then what?”
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company does not find more success.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [it’s these types of people] that end up leading businesses and product-specialized staff are pushed away from decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine designing a good product compared to a bad product - the manual work required.
This is what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire IT industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They snatched defeat to victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
"A huge part of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises to be made... Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made out of personal taste. It is about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring these things to the product that you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
