How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines indicates how pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies have destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has become an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with violations of campaign funding related to covering an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who have lived the story will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton set off by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at school and university tests are legion.
There have been instances where teachers have given students the test responses in order to be clearly visible on their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many deceptions do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to shout out: "I got you," the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades from prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, particularly in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been demystified.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don’t stammer, blush, or aren’t always agitated.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can uncover the truth by examining the statement structure, facial micro-expressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include including hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are skilled at reading others well, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more lies "centered on themselves" while women tell more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "establishing benchmark data".
This helps to provide a point of reference for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, the laughter, the voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally shakes their feet constantly so as not to throw unfair accusations when you see them shaking their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues to misleading verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Misleading people can immobilize the upper body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet to the door, lean toward an exit, change posture significantly, or present a "post-interview" relief - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is completed just to seek to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson skidded using the past while pretending that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Misleading individuals may also use distant language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember right... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
