Climate adversity has slowed the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has declined and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-called change, which generated high expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the economic adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange for the deterioration of the main indicators.
Low temperatures in February, aside from causing trillion-dollar losses for the agricultural sector, limited the state economy's opportunities for growth, caused overall economic activity to contract by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost allocations issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, 78.03 percent of which suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment of the state during the first three quarters of the year is a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand, a thousand.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
“What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who make dollars illicitly it is not easy for them to work to earn them, to invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes pointed out that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because when they enter they already have a lot of difficulty finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the labor market is worsened by considering the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population employed in this state work there without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the gap for the state is the low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of the Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which stands at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
IED contraction
Apart from declining economic activity and rising unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the FDI of the State reached $630 thousand 697, representing a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government has a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt (disambiguation)
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the Government of the State requested in July at the public congress the approval of a loan of 3 trillion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State congress was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November no profit was observed.
Reactions
For representatives of the employers' sector, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés demonstrates a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of the Sinaloa economy during this year has really been very poor, we have to work intensively to recover the ground that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our effort, we have to align the effort of all and especially the good already synchronized performance of this new government team, hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year have held back the state’s economy and restricted its yield and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, among which frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state to productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that we unleash the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in how public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that a lot of work has been done and the Government is aware that there is still a lot to do," he said.
