Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the air crash in which lost his life the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake and other seven people
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven others lost their lives indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations done in the impact zone do not report the appearance of ground parts.
“In a research it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact occurred structurally.
“The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a slope of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For the moment, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as quickly as possible; but the investigation can take a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, general manager of Aéroports et Services Auxiliaires, assured that the moment of impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was operating at cruise speed and this happened on a soft ascending ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he said.
During the press conference, the holder of the TBS, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned adequate conditions for take-off, and as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-rise cloud layers.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew sought a lower-height area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a reduced area:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The model of dispersal of the aircraft remains suggests that the helicopter collided with the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion have been detected:
In the location of the disaster there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of any type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9 thousand 200 feet above average sea level, the ground had a slope that goes from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he possibly disarticulated himself along his journey.
The information provides evidence that appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful searching in an area wider than the encircled location, around the accident, no dispersed parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and youth; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people, called 'Children's and Adolescent Obesity Genetics' protocol that will have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialty Hospital of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre d'Investigation et d'<0xC3><0x89>tudes Avancées (Cinvestav) of the Institut Polytechnique National (IPN).
The investigation invites the right and non-right population to participate in the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence to minors is carried out every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Sport Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the target of gathering 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sport Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sport Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the purpose of this investigation and the e to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the implementation of the specific questionnaires related to food.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics will be applied to all participants (people associated with childhood obesity are being identified).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of health professionals' concern for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 reported that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 per cent in obesity and in the case of girls, of 47 per cent; in the case of overweight there was also a dramatic increase," stressed the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population is different from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American, a 30 percent European and a five percent African heredity and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translate into the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which makes it possible to detect if they are overweight or obese.
Ila even said that the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, the doctors give it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measures and lifestyle changes that they must make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying in front of the TV most of the day and using means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - meat pie with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement was resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 blackcurrants each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Zone, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the tarpaulin is adequate, the blackcurrants could be reduced or even reduced.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Blackcurrants, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and consequently, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The CF researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México were mostly covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles pass there generating forces, this allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If there was modified asphalt, it would spread better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt layer, he says, is placed a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes blackcurrants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first that gets spoiled is the rolling film and only subsequently is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicle load is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrants and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the vehicle load and ensure its satisfaction, to avoid frequent formation of blackcurrants.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair blackcurrants easily and without having to use high temperatures.
