Thus was the work of the person from Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A Cali typist has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, a CTI typist from Cali went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the FARC’s supreme leader, “Alfonso Cano,” by confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists working in the local offices of the CTI, this week it was the "availability" tour of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to reach the place where the corpses were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking appropriate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of frictional skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who ran the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the location of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like an area farmer, without glasses and much leaner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a picker and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse to those on the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
Searching for the Imprint
For a typist from Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don’t know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin of error, that can be crucial in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying the corpses, typists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present fake ID cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and search them in the database.
The researcher recounted that in a case of theft he had to remove a part of a wall from a house, because in that place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate areas to take a fingerprint from, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in different thefts," he recalls.
Fingerprints can also remove or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently a dead man was found, with bottles of drink around him.
Intermittently, it was determined that a parent may be a suspect in the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee he's the killer, it puts him on the scene.
A CTI typist explained that “fingerprints are extracted from objects with chemical or physical reagents.”
When they appear, a sampler or strip is used to collect them.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the database of the declining, or to the National Civil Registry.
“The problem is that there are still a lot of undocumented Colombians,” the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
As everything that shines is not gold, everything you touch does not necessarily become an imprint.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
The “indignados” challenge the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters were rushing in front of Zuccotti Square to camp there.
