The members of the Occupy Wall Street movement defied the New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to re-enter, through a court order, Manhattan’s place, where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another Big Apple park.
Hundreds of protesters were rushing in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to access thanks to a court order that allows the 'indignados' to camp again in this place, while the other side of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new stops.
“Our idea is that if the court doesn’t allow us to camp in the square again, we’re going to settle in another place and we’ll continue the legal fight to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful protests,” said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray detailed that the “outraged” response to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the place and allowing protesters to stay in the camp.
In addition, the “indignados” occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which links New York and New Jersey, owned by the Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some protesters, even though Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
