Some protesters displaced so far were carrying and distributing copies of this court order at that time and they were even handing it over to the officers who were monitoring the square, which caused 'certain small clashes,' said Bray, who denounced the fact that some officials beat the protesters.
The court order prohibits authorities from evacuating members of Occupy Wall Street or enforcing “laws issued after the beginning of the occupation or prohibiting protesters from re-entering the park with tents or other properties they used previously.”
Mayor Bloomberg told reporters that because of the court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and protesters, but warned them that local laws do not allow them to move in with tents and sleeping bags.
The city councilman personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn in Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the protesters were 'violating the law'.
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the place because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to break the laws and in some cases, to harm other people" because "some shops had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"This morning's evacuation at dawn has been disgusting and shows that Bloomberg is basically more interested in defending the financial interests of American workers than in defending those of American workers," the spokesman added, accusing the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression."
