Japan Reborn After Earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the spiral of decline at the beginning of March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, recovering even after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the country since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Government of Tokyo have estimated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September were used to definitively turn the page: GDP rose 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase since January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decline in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use deficiencies to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The Stigma of the Yen
Tokyo reverted to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refuge values" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the forecast troubles of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic buoyancy is determined by the health of major technology groups.
Toyota and Sony, for example, blamed the yen for their weak results between July and September.
As markets continue to be based in the EU’s peripheral countries, Yoshihiko Noda’s government does not lower its guard.
"We need to monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said Motohisa Furukawa, Secretary of State for Economic Policy.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging at all.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) noted that the majority of member countries showed clearer signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points of the global economy has highlighted that major powers are being curbed.
Because it dropped four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
The Eurozone was even below the average, which is at level 100, dropping eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
