As in other cases, the advertising effects seem somewhat disproportionate to the reality of work stoppage fraud.
It has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives since 2002, which have most often paid off.
The French are not sicker than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us first look at the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than €237 million in daily allowances were awarded in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditure in 2008, with 11.3 billion euros.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity leave and occupational accidents, and 54% concerned sick leave, or 6.2 billion euros.
This is 2.5% of health care expenditure.
In 2010, the French experienced an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
Another survey, published in 2007 by career management website Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken any sick days.
Another study, this time from the Health Insurance, states that in 2010, 37% of illness stoppages were of a duration of less than 8 days, 22% of 8 to 14 days, 15% of 15 days to one month, 15% of one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more prone to stopping work than elsewhere.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) fluctuated between 10% and 11% in France, compared with 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Sick leave fraud represents very little in the face of black work.
As for fraud, it only reaches a small scale.
The tightening of legislation since 2002 means that checks on sick leave for more than 45 days are systematic.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million checks, the CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 made for short-term stoppages were "unjustified or too long", or 37,050 cases.
In the case of arrests of more than 45 days, systematically monitored, there were 11% of cases "inappropriate or unjustified" out of 1.2 million, or 132,000.
A total of 169,000 "unjustified" cases, out of several million employees who have had sick leave.
A figure that represents very little compared, for example, to that of black work.
According to UMP MP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, this would represent 9 to 15 billion euros of tax loss per year, more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud to the latter.
