Euthanasia and assisted suicide must be legalized, says expert committee
Canadians Live in Denial of Death, Royal Society of Canada Report
When it comes to palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the findings of an imposing report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts from a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow for assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, with a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries on the planet.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has spawned a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medically or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts commissioned by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Overall, the country's highest rate is in Quebec, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospitals.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the report draws conclusions that go against the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where such approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that such decriminalization leads to abuses in enforcement, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on non-competent or non-consenting persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signer of the report, said yesterday in a teleconference that more cases of these outbursts would be found precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
