“Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal,” says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians support euthanasia
85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would allow end-of-life people to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid poll.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of older or disabled people are of less value.
As for people who have committed assisted suicide, 41% of respondents estimate that they should not be prosecuted.
When it comes to maintaining or discontinuing care for a patient, the situation is less clear, say the report's authors.
Also, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it be stated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The expert committee also calls for health professionals to be trained in their duty to respect a refusal of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
When it comes to palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer cases.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee requests that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations from other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the Royal Society of Canada's expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described the position of the experts signatories of the report as "extreme", among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to terminally ill patients.
"This opens the door to a situation where anyone who would be tired of life and who would be over 18 could ask for help in suicide," said Deschamps, who had consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr. Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
“In society,” he said, “there are beacons and constraints.”
Health law expert Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she called "pro-euthanasia manifesto."
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, particularly disputes the data in the report on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, namely in the Netherlands and Oregon.
