Monti demands time from markets and sacrifices from Italians
The future head of the Italian government, Mario Monti, has demanded some time from the markets to train his team and implement a program, which will contain "sacrifice", in order to recover the credibility lost in the last months of the Berlusconi government.
The former European Commissioner was in talks with political parties yesterday before meeting with trade unions and employers today.
He is expected to set up a relatively small cabinet composed of technocrats outside Parliament.
"Monti spoke of an important program with a lot of sacrifices," Francesco Nucara, a member of one of the many small parliamentary groups involved in the talks, said after meeting with the president-designate.
House Speaker Gianfranco Fini said he expects Mario Monti to ask Parliament for a vote of confidence by Friday to ensure the new government has sufficient support.
The consultations will conclude with the presentation by Mr Monti of a short list, probably of a dozen ministers, to the Head of State, Giorgio Napolitano.
Monti commented on the nervousness of the stock and bond markets yesterday, asking for time.
In "democracy, there are precise deadlines" for preparing a government and its agenda, he said, saying "certainly the markets will be patient and understand".
His appointment by the president had initially been welcomed by the markets, but the concern regained the upper hand, notably after an unexpected fall in industrial production in the euro area in September.
The prime minister-designate is expected to form a team of mostly technocrats, although he stressed that he would like to include "politics".
The new government will last until 2013, the date of the next legislative elections, he said.
