Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas.
If there is a subject that cannot be addressed on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is healthy that an election meeting is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and on nuclear issues.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic evolution will result in a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless we deprive a huge portion of the world’s population of a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will need to be addressed in order to continue to produce electricity permanently, not to mention the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just wants to build only the latest generation of power plants.
Conversely, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States, on the other hand, decided after Fukushima to add a unit to its park by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, a leap in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all of these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to be meditated.
European champion of wind power, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; by virtue of which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power illusory.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not manifest a principled opposition to this energy, polls show.
Let us recall that our country's energy policy has helped to build an industrial sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it trains a galaxy of specialized SMEs in international markets and makes them very creating non-relocatable jobs.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear, it would be to sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing as a skin of grief the 6 billion euros per year of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to operate for sixty years when its manufacturer’s decline would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miracle electricity production, nor does there exist a diabolical one.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have an Autorité de sécurité that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants as well as the Flamanville construction site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human errors caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and a cooperation between the French and German security authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all the electricians eager to build a power plant, the stopping of its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to the competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them the free path to seize the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy package for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such a crucial debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23) proclaiming in the passage that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant servers".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million migrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on both the left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be accorded to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may pay off electorally; but it is economically very costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and unemployment in countries that receive employment.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and hampering employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are likely to replace national workers, especially low-skilled workers, putting downward pressure on their wages.
However, experience has shown that immigrants are in reality much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly working in sectors with a shortage of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the offer of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country that has a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a large proportion of naturalized immigrants among the US Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of 150,000 euros to public budgets on average over his entire life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to go and look for the missing growth points "with his teeth".
The teeth in question, used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought
Democracy is a precious good; it is also a fragile good.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would suffice for democracy to triumph over its enemies for good, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little One", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an instrument of oppression, as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis of the Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is equally and first and foremost a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the Greek real-fake referendum will have had the value of twofold revealing in this regard: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized as necessary and in dispersed order.
A whitewash to the absolute European monarch or a leap together in the void of nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts, but a common, full-fledged, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - we can no longer stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that abides by the dictates of the markets and the rating agencies, that suffers from its powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole that slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to restore people's sovereignty to the management of the European project.
Because it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
Outcome from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After a long struggle against this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic government.
Oh, yeah.
But to think without a stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage of European integration.
To make the Republic in France, it had to "make" the Republicans.
The revolution in the interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more politically democratic Europe, a genuine European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
