The Nord Stream, new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia through the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, to the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the West-European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe each year via a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second tube is due to be completed by the end of 2012, enabling a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas to be delivered, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site feels like victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land crossing by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has triumphed over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the heavily gas-consuming, wealthy Western countries whose deposits are declining.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us organically," Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed when inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how politically and economically the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine tube is made of concrete-clad steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"A hundred had to be abducted or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts along its entire length: neither valve, nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project leaders renounced it while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state company permanently set up off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have planned welds to leak every 100,000 years.
The gas pipeline is monitored by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it provides accurate information about possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars on departure, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies created a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty renewable years, all gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided by shareholders for 30% and by bank loans for 70%.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach €7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay their own costs, as only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit gate.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificity of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
Yet the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design notebook but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (mole skin) which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back to life an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces sold.
It is far from the confidential production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a portrait-robot of the buyer, because the notebook appeals to the businessman as well as the student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its early days, has almost 100 employees today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city center and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also released a leopard cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a range of supports.
A success that made envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled begins today.
Despite a proactive public policy put in place in 2005, the unemployment rate of people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
“No,” stresses <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
" The progress made over the last 15 years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, there is still a lot to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before entering employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with an average of 38%.
In short, these are all criteria that complicate the return to employment, and which "are the root of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit workers with disabilities.
That's for the objective brakes.
The unsaid remains, the mindsets that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the interviewed managers have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual disabilities ".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of 1987.
The latest figures, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body in charge of collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
